    * I am currently involved in the project “Tourism and World Heritage,” part of the UNESCO UniTwin Network on Culture, Tourism and Development, coordinated in Brazil by the University of São Paulo (USP).  
    *   
    * The project's main objective is to organize an academic field trip to Chapada do Araripe (Ceará) from June 1st to 7th, 2025, aimed at preparing a nomination dossier for the inscription of the region as a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Chapada do Araripe was added to the UNESCO Tentative List in February 2024 and has hosted a UNESCO Global Geopark since 2006, the first in the Americas.  
    *   
    * In addition to the workshop’s own activities, the UniTwin team is expected to take part in the 6th edition of the seminar “Heritage Providing Humanity”, organized by Fundação Casa Grande since 2019\. This participation is part of broader efforts to support a community-based (“bottom-up”) approach to the nomination process, fostering articulation at both local and national levels.

      As part of the preparation for the 2025 international workshop in Cariri (CE), I contribute to institutional communication and intercultural coordination between USP, Fundação Casa Grande, and international UniTwin partners. The project promotes ethical tourism, heritage preservation, and inclusive territorial development through dialogue between researchers and local communities.

* The Domestic Care Work Performed By Children and Adolescents and Its Visibility on Brazilian Digital News Portals  
* The Domestic Care Work Performed By Children and Adolescents and Its Visibility on Brazilian Digital News Portals  
* ago de 2022 \- out de 2023  
* ago de 2022 \- out de 2023  
  * ![Logo da empresa Universidade de São Paulo][image3]  
  * Associado(s) a Universidade de São Paulo  
  * Associado(s) a Universidade de São Paulo  
    * I participated in a scientific research project developed at the School of Arts, Sciences and Humanities of the University of São Paulo (EACH-USP), as part of the course ACH1603 – Knowledge Production in Leisure and Tourism. Our research analyzed how major Brazilian digital news portals portray domestic care work performed by children and adolescents, especially through the lenses of gender, race, class, and public policy.  
    *   
    * The study aimed to examine how the media either exposes or naturalizes child domestic labor, and how these portrayals intensified during the COVID-19 pandemic. This was part of a broader discussion within the field of Public Policy Management.  
    *   
    * My contributions to the project included:

      \- Conducting content analysis of 71 news articles from major media outlets (Folha, Estadão, UOL, CNN, BBC, among others);  
      \- Coding qualitative data using Bardin’s content analysis methodology;  
      \- Organizing data in spreadsheets and producing analytical graphs to synthesize findings;  
      \- Assisting in literature review, hypothesis formulation, and indicator development;  
      \- Co-authoring the final report and supporting academic discussions within the research group.

      This work was officially published and presented at the 31st International Symposium on Scientific and Technological Initiation at USP (SIICUSP), under registration number 2359, ISSN 2448-072X, contributing to the thematic area of Public Policy Management.

      Participating in this project allowed me to explore the intersection of social inequality, media analysis, and policy evaluation, while refining my skills in academic research, critical thinking, and collaborative teamwork.  
    * I participated in a scientific research project developed at the School of Arts, Sciences and Humanities of the University of São Paulo (EACH-USP), as part of the course ACH1603 – Knowledge Production in Leisure and Tourism. Our research analyzed how major Brazilian digital news portals portray domestic care work performed by children and adolescents, especially through the lenses of gender, race, class, and public policy. The study aimed to examine how the media either exposes or naturalizes child domestic labor, and how these portrayals intensified during the COVID-19 pandemic. This was part of a broader discussion within the field of Public Policy Management. My contributions to the project included: \- Conducting content analysis of 71 news articles from major media outlets (Folha, Estadão, UOL, CNN, BBC, among others); \- Coding qualitative data using Bardin’s content analysis methodology; \- Organizing data in spreadsheets and producing analytical graphs to synthesize findings; \- Assisting in literature review, hypothesis formulation, and indicator development; \- Co-authoring the final report and supporting academic discussions within the research group. This work was officially published and presented at the 31st International Symposium on Scientific and Technological Initiation at USP (SIICUSP), under registration number 2359, ISSN 2448-072X, contributing to the thematic area of Public Policy Management. Participating in this project allowed me to explore the intersection of social inequality, media analysis, and policy evaluation, while refining my skills in academic research, critical thinking, and collaborative teamwork.
